
# Workflow 1. Land use change transitions to crease baseline map + manegment schedule

##Step 1 – Input land-use and TRC forestry maps
Resources:
General Land-use map (2015) 
Forestry maps for 2004, 2018, and 2021 (LU_2004,LU_2018, LU_2021)
Forestry-priority soils map (MGAP).

##Step 2 – Harmonise land-use classes and clean attribute tables
First we cleaned attribute tables for all input layers. Then we used the defined land-use classification scheme to assigned a unique land-use code per class ( see Table 2).
##Step 3 – Union all time slices to create a multi-year change map.
We generated the union map using the union tool in QGIS to merge: 2004 forestry map, 2015 general land use (with ESC), 2018 forestry map, 2021 forestry map. This allowed to create polygons representing unique combinations of land use across all layers (homogeneposu numeric coeds). The union result layer is LU_union_2004_2015_2018_2021.shp 
##Step 4 – Assign temporal land-use codes and create 13 final classes
We analysed the union layer to identify unique temporal sequences (e.g. pine forest → pine forest, grassland → pine forest, euca or pine forest → grassland, see table in the manuscript). Using this transitions we assigned a new land-use code that summarises the temporal trajectory for each polygon. Mapped these trajectories using nmeric codes after map union we obtained a total to 13 final classes (see Table 3 in the manuscript appednix).
Resources can be found in Figshare https://doi.org/10.6084/m9.figshare.30856865 
